#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:2
#: ec640fafcdb6441fae87571d2cf24a9f
msgid "Diffusion"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:4
#: 80936234a3d14c70bb89904a0ede882f
msgid ""
"Two transient examples in ``examples/diffusion/``: a linear heat equation"
" with implicit Euler time stepping (``heat/heat.py``) and a nonlinear "
"phase-field problem solved by Newton's method at each timestep (``allen-"
"cahn/ac.py``). Together they exercise both the linear time-stepping "
"pattern from :doc:`../user_guide/time_integration` and the nonlinear / "
"Newton pattern from :doc:`../user_guide/linear_solvers`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:14
#: 1c126fe67f8d4d078fd9d9511c1e5dd5
msgid "2D heat equation — ``heat/heat.py``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:16
#: 3a11097fc55c43a695de237b8f70c596
msgid "The strong form is"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:18
#: 3be135fd10cc4476b3d313c60e15b73e
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"u_t \\;=\\; D^2\\, \\Delta u\n"
"\\quad \\text{in } \\Omega,\n"
"\\qquad u = 0 \\text{ on } \\partial\\Omega,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:24
#: 351e9093f742420ebbdb41650c7023b5
msgid ""
"on the unit square with a multi-frequency Fourier-series initial "
"condition from :class:`~tensormesh.dataset.HeatMultiFrequency`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:28
#: 8c634ffefedd4b79902627c5b16dc3d8
msgid "Backward (implicit) Euler turns each step into a linear solve:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:30
#: 8fd53673c0764a01ad2ccc52fb150941
#, python-brace-format
msgid "(M + \\Delta t\\, D^2\\, A)\\, U^{n+1} \\;=\\; M\\, U^{n},"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:34
#: 97e87d6d51924419b38cd765f2cfbf84
msgid ""
"where :math:`M` is the mass matrix and :math:`A` is the Laplace "
"stiffness. The script assembles both once and reuses them across steps:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:38
#: 34597b2befe14b8aa457e7821a85091a
msgid "examples/diffusion/heat/heat.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:67
#: 73bb549eba144583bf1bc085179691aa
msgid "A few choices reflect the user-guide patterns:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:69
#: 26003baeb24b4c988badf11d3c2f199c
msgid ""
"**Quadratic triangles** (``order=2, element_type=\"tri\"``) — heat "
"diffusion is smooth on the interior, so order-2 elements give a much "
"sharper match to the analytical solution at the same mesh size."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:73
#: 6891f1d7a02449be82899b6434973073
msgid ""
"**One assembly, many solves.** ``K`` and ``K_`` are built before the "
"loop. Each step only does a matrix-vector ``M @ U``, a condense-RHS, and "
"a solve — so the bulk of the cost is the per-step linear solve."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:77
#: 5e2057acfabe43088ae7ce909bbd059c
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"**Comparison with truth.** "
":meth:`~tensormesh.dataset.HeatMultiFrequency.solution` returns the "
"analytical solution at each time, and ``mesh.plot({\"prediction\": Us, "
"\"ground truth\": Us_gt}, save_path=\"heat.mp4\", dt=dt)`` writes a side-"
"by-side animation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:83
#: cac5a092a7bc417ca4f359912eef65b1
msgid ""
"The same scheme expressed with TensorMesh's "
":class:`~tensormesh.ode.builtin.ImplicitLinearEuler` integrator is shown "
"in :doc:`../user_guide/time_integration`; this script is the lower-level "
"\"by hand\" version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:96
#: 82aae47feade450384a905fc14e1e287
msgid ""
"*Output of* ``heat.py``: *FEM prediction (left) vs analytical truth "
"(right) over the time window. The two stay visually identical to the eye,"
" with the maximum nodal error decaying smoothly as the backward-Euler "
"step damps the highest Fourier mode.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:103
#: 720350f9e50f455cbec3120dda801501
msgid "Allen-Cahn phase field — ``allen-cahn/ac.py``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:105
#: 3c31d39e51f841879985d7b891c65e73
msgid "The Allen-Cahn equation is the textbook nonlinear phase-field model:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:108
#: d011f7bd26dd48f9bb27ecaba8c35af6
msgid "u_t \\;=\\; \\Delta u + \\varepsilon^2\\, u\\, (1 - u^2),"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:112
#: f2fde19c269c4b3e9fbd3eb976ece9d6
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"with natural (no-flux) boundary conditions and a smooth initial condition"
" that evolves toward the binary phases :math:`u \\in \\{-1, 1\\}`. With "
":math:`\\varepsilon = 220` and :math:`\\Delta t = 10^{-6}`, the "
"nonlinearity is stiff enough that an explicit integrator would require "
"infeasibly small steps; the script uses **implicit Euler plus Newton "
"iteration**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:119
#: da0572c34a9b4d8c9add70c39405f091
msgid "At each time step Newton solves the residual"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:121
#: c4eb6c79a14740388a180dbd437cb6c1
msgid ""
"R(c) \\;=\\;\n"
"\\frac{c - c_\\text{old}}{\\Delta t}\\, v\n"
"\\;+\\; D(c)\\, \\nabla v \\cdot \\nabla c\n"
"\\;-\\; f(c)\\, v\n"
"\\;\\xrightarrow{!}\\; 0,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:129
#: 51f71e9266394a3a9159a7ef7aab3cda
msgid ""
"with Jacobian :math:`K = \\partial R / \\partial c` linearized around the"
" current iterate. Both are written as TensorMesh assemblers so the "
"pattern is the same as a linear solve:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:133
#: fbbe8147d6594150bb7505cbac0b07bb
msgid "examples/diffusion/allen-cahn/ac.py (essence)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:163
#: 6a1899a64b4448e1bb5ef3bbdb4983aa
msgid "Two things that make this easy to write:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:165
#: d96a9343ab7e402fbd4534af4f7dff55
msgid ""
"**Per-iterate parameters via** ``point_data``. The current iterate ``c`` "
"and the previous timestep's solution ``cold`` are passed by name into "
"both ``forward`` methods — exactly the argument-dispatch contract "
"documented in :doc:`../user_guide/forms`. There is no per-quadrature-"
"point Python loop."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:171
#: be4d11db46014d1c9194e2f000ddf475
msgid ""
"**Reassemble each iteration.** Because ``K`` depends on ``c`` (through "
"``D(c)``, ``df(c)``), it has to be rebuilt every Newton iteration. That "
"is intentional — assembly is cheap on the GPU, and the alternative "
"(computing analytical Jacobians by hand) would require pages of "
"additional code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:177
#: 524d87674d8d4e0e9532384d699a003f
msgid ""
"For nonlinear problems where you would rather hand the whole residual to "
"a packaged driver, ``torch-sla``'s ``SparseMatrix.nonlinear_solve`` "
"(Newton / Picard / Anderson with Armijo line search; see "
":doc:`../user_guide/linear_solvers`) takes a single residual closure, "
"builds the Jacobian via autograd, and gives you a correct adjoint "
"backward through the converged solution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/diffusion.rst:192
#: 4f80c9912cd148ab8289934f3e70bd9f
msgid ""
"*Output of* ``ac.py``: *the order parameter* :math:`\\varphi` *evolving "
"on the unit square. Starting from random noise it rapidly coarsens into "
"the two equilibrium phases (* :math:`\\varphi=\\pm1` *), with diffuse "
"interfaces of width set by* :math:`\\varepsilon`. *Each frame is one "
"resolved Newton solve.*"
msgstr ""

